1
00:00:00,100 --> 00:00:06,250
(Luke 2:11): "And when Jesus had become twelve years of age, etc."

2
00:00:06,200 --> 00:00:17,300
We read in the gospel that when our Lord was twelve years old he went with Joseph and Mary to Jerusalem into the temple; and when they went out, Jesus remained behind in the temple without their knowing it.

3
00:00:17,300 --> 00:00:27,850
And when they reached home and missed him, they sought him among acquaintances and among strangers, among their kindred, and among the multitude, and found him not; they had lost him in the crowd.

4
00:00:27,850 --> 00:00:35,875
So there was nothing for it but to return whence they were come; and when they got back to their starting-point, into the temple, there they found him.

5
00:00:35,875 --> 00:00:44,537
If thou wilt find this noble birth, verily thou must quit the multitude and return to the starting-point, into the ground out of which thou art come.

6
00:00:44,537 --> 00:00:59,762
The powers of the soul and their works, these are the multitude: memory, understanding and will; these all diversify thee, therefore thou must leave them all: sensible perception, imagination and everything wherein thou findest thyself and hast thyself in view.

7
00:00:59,762 --> 00:01:04,725
Thereafter thou mayest find this birth, but, believe me, not otherwise.

8
00:01:04,725 --> 00:01:11,750
He has never been found among friends, nor among kindred nor acquaintances, there rather does one lose him altogether.

9
00:01:11,750 --> 00:01:30,937
Now the question arises, whether this birth is to be found in anything which, albeit relating to God, is nevertheless taken in from without through the senses, in any presentment of God as good, wise, or compassionate, or whatever intellect can conceive of divinity: whether this birth is to be found in any such-like things?

10
00:01:30,937 --> 00:01:32,537
In truth, no!

11
00:01:32,537 --> 00:01:47,537
for, although good and godlike, they are nevertheless introduced from without through the senses; all must well up from within, out of God, if this birth is to shine with a really clear light, and thy own work must lie over, every faculty serving his ends not thine own.

12
00:01:47,537 --> 00:01:52,562
If this work is to be done, God alone must do it, and thou must undergo it.

13
00:01:52,562 --> 00:01:59,962
Where from thy willing and knowing thou truly goest out, God with his knowing surely and willingly goes in and shines there clearly.

14
00:01:59,962 --> 00:02:04,725
Where God thus knows himself thy knowledge is of no avail and cannot stand.

15
00:02:04,725 --> 00:02:25,025
Do not fondly imagine that thy reason can grow to the knowledge of God; that God shall shine in thee divinely no natural light can help to bring about; it must be utterly extinguished and go out of itself altogether, then God can shine in with his light bringing back with him everything thou wentest out of and a thousandfold more, besides the new form containing it all.

16
00:02:25,025 --> 00:02:27,800
Of this we have an allegory in the gospel.

17
00:02:27,800 --> 00:02:37,125
When our Lord had talked so friendly with the Gentile woman at the well, she left her pitcher there, and running to the town announced to her people that the true Messiah was come.

18
00:02:37,125 --> 00:02:42,362
The people, not believing her report, went out with her to see him for themselves.

19
00:02:42,362 --> 00:02:48,862
Then said they unto her, ‘Now we believe, not because of thy words, but because we have seen him in person.

20
00:02:48,862 --> 00:02:55,562
Verily, neither by any creaturely science nor by thine own wisdom canst thou be brought to know God divinely.

21
00:02:55,562 --> 00:03:02,887
To know God God-fashion, thy knowledge must change into downright unknowing, to a forgetting of thyself and every creature.

22
00:03:02,887 --> 00:03:10,225
Now haply thou wilt say: ‘Prithee, Sir, what is the use of my intellect if it has to be inert and altogether idle?

23
00:03:10,225 --> 00:03:15,812
Is it my best plan to raise my mind to the unknowing knowing which obviously cannot be anything?

24
00:03:15,812 --> 00:03:21,050
For if I knew anything it would not be ignorance, nor should I be idle and destitute.

25
00:03:21,050 --> 00:03:23,775
Must I remain in total darkness?

26
00:03:23,775 --> 00:03:25,300
Aye, surely!

27
00:03:25,300 --> 00:03:30,150
Thou canst do no better than take up thy abode in total darkness and ignorance.

28
00:03:30,150 --> 00:03:31,512
Alas, Sir!

29
00:03:31,512 --> 00:03:34,825
must everything go then, and is there no return?

30
00:03:34,825 --> 00:03:36,400
No, truly!

31
00:03:36,400 --> 00:03:38,537
By rights there is no return.

32
00:03:38,537 --> 00:03:40,575
But what is this darkness?

33
00:03:40,575 --> 00:03:43,037
What does it mean, what is its name?

34
00:03:43,204 --> 00:03:54,641
It can only be called a potential receptivity, which, however, is not altogether wanting in nor indigent of (real) being: the merely potential conception wherein thou shalt be perfected.

35
00:03:54,591 --> 00:03:56,916
Hence there is no return from it.

36
00:03:56,916 --> 00:04:03,216
An thou returnest it is not because of any truth; it is either the senses, the world or the devil.

37
00:04:03,216 --> 00:04:11,479
And persisting in this turning back, thou dost inevitably lapse into sin and art liable to backslide so far as to have the eternal fall.

38
00:04:11,479 --> 00:04:18,191
Wherefore there is no turning back, only a pressing forward and following up this possibility to its fulfilment.

39
00:04:18,191 --> 00:04:21,354
It never rests until fulfilled with all being.

40
00:04:21,354 --> 00:04:29,366
As matter never rests until fulfilled with every possible form, so intellect never rests till it is filled to the full of its capacity.

41
00:04:29,366 --> 00:04:36,479
Concerning this a heathen master says: ‘Nature has nothing swifter than the heavens which surpass all else in swiftness.

42
00:04:36,479 --> 00:04:39,316
But surely the mind of man outstrips them.

43
00:04:39,316 --> 00:04:51,579
Given that it retains its vigour and stays undemeaned and undismembered by what is base and gross, it can outstrip high heaven nor slacken till the summit, where it is fed and cherished by the Arch-Good, by God himself.

44
00:04:51,579 --> 00:05:04,491
How profitable then to ensue this possibility, for by keeping thyself empty and bare, merely tracking and following and giving up thyself to this darkness and ignorance without turning back, thou mayest well win that which is all things.

45
00:05:04,491 --> 00:05:09,604
And the more thou art barren of thyself and ignorant of things the nearer thou art thereto.

46
00:05:09,604 --> 00:05:16,379
Of this barrenness it is written in Hosea: ‘I will lead my friend into the desert and will speak to her in her heart.

47
00:05:16,379 --> 00:05:23,979
The genuine Word of eternity is spoken only in eternity, where man is a desert and alien to himself and multiplicity.

48
00:05:23,979 --> 00:05:31,954
For this desolate self-estrangement the prophet longed, saying: ‘Who will give me the wings of a dove that I may fly away and be at rest!

49
00:05:31,954 --> 00:05:34,404
Where shall I find peace and rest?

50
00:05:34,404 --> 00:05:39,629
Verily in rejection, in desolation and estrangement from all creatures.

51
00:05:39,629 --> 00:05:47,054
Wherefore David says: ‘I had rather be an abject in the house of my God than have honour and riches in the tabernacles of sinners.

52
00:05:47,054 --> 00:05:57,816
Now haply thou wilt say: ‘Alas, Sir, after all, is it necessary to be barren and estranged from everything, outward and inward: the powers and their works, must all go?

53
00:05:57,816 --> 00:06:09,079
It is a grievous matter for a man thus to be left by God without support; for God to thus augment his misery, neither enlightening nor encouraging nor working in him, for that is what your teaching means.

54
00:06:09,079 --> 00:06:20,454
For a person in such downright nothingness would it not be better to be doing something to beguile the gloom and desolation; to pray or read or go to church or else make shift by working at some useful occupation?

55
00:06:20,454 --> 00:06:26,066
No, be sure of this: absolute stillness, absolute idleness is best of all.

56
00:06:26,066 --> 00:06:31,029
Know that thou canst not without harm exchange this state for any other whatsoever.

57
00:06:31,029 --> 00:06:36,454
Fain wouldst thou partly fit thyself and let God partly fit thee, but that cannot be.

58
00:06:36,454 --> 00:06:41,829
Art never so quick to think of this fitness and desire it, God forestalls thee always.

59
00:06:41,829 --> 00:06:55,766
But granting, what is impossible, that it is shared: that the preparation for this working or infusion is jointly his and thine, know then, that God is bound to act, to pour himself out (into thee) as soon as ever he shall find thee ready.

60
00:06:55,766 --> 00:07:03,916
Think not it is with God as with a human carpenter, who works or works not as he chooses, who can do or leave undone at his good pleasure.

61
00:07:03,916 --> 00:07:15,679
It is not thus with God; but finding thee ready he is obliged to act, to overflow into thee; just as the sun must needs burst forth when the air is bright and clear, and is unable to contain itself.

62
00:07:15,679 --> 00:07:25,079
Forsooth, it were a very grave defect in God if, finding thee so empty and so bare, he wrought no excellent work in thee nor primed thee with glorious gifts.

63
00:07:25,228 --> 00:07:35,365
In the same sense philosophers declare that the instant the child-stuff is ready in the mother’s womb, God pours into the body its living spirit, that is, the soul the form of the body.

64
00:07:35,315 --> 00:07:38,903
It is one flash, the being-ready and the pouring-in.

65
00:07:38,903 --> 00:07:46,840
Nature reaching her summit, God dispenses his grace: the instant the spirit is ready God enters without hesitation or delay.

66
00:07:46,840 --> 00:07:56,290
In the book of Mystery it is written that our Lord offers himself to men: ‘Behold I stand at the door and knock, waiting for someone to let me in, with him will I sup.

67
00:07:56,290 --> 00:08:05,578
Thou needst not seek him here or there, he is no further off than at the door of thy heart; there he stands lingering, awaiting whoever is ready to open and let him in.

68
00:08:05,578 --> 00:08:11,303
Thou needst not call to him afar, he waits much more impatiently than thou for thee to open to him.

69
00:08:11,303 --> 00:08:17,428
He longs for thee a thousandfold more urgently than thou for him: one point the opening and the entering.

70
00:08:17,428 --> 00:08:20,715
Thou wilt say, perhaps: ‘How can that be?

71
00:08:20,715 --> 00:08:22,653
I have no inkling of him.

72
00:08:22,653 --> 00:08:26,578
Know, that to find him is not in thy power but in his.

73
00:08:26,578 --> 00:08:31,190
He discovers himself when he chooses and he hides himself too when he will.

74
00:08:31,190 --> 00:08:40,540
This is what Christ meant when he said to Nicodemus, ‘The spirit breatheth where he will; thou hearest his voice, but knowest not whence he cometh nor whither he goeth.

75
00:08:40,540 --> 00:08:44,365
This is a contradiction: ‘Thou hearest but knowest not.

76
00:08:44,365 --> 00:08:45,965
By hearing we know.

77
00:08:45,965 --> 00:08:52,765
Christ meant that through hearing it is imbibed or absorbed; as though to say: thou receivest it but unawares.

78
00:08:52,765 --> 00:09:00,315
For know, God cannot leave anything void and unfilled; that aught should be empty or void is not to be endured by nature’s God.

79
00:09:00,315 --> 00:09:06,640
An thou seemest, therefore, not to find him and to be wholly empty of him, yet that is not the case.

80
00:09:06,640 --> 00:09:16,565
For were there any emptiness under heaven, whatever it might be, or great or small, the heavens must either draw it up to them or, bending downwards, fill it with themselves.

81
00:09:16,565 --> 00:09:21,353
God, nature’s lord, on no account permits of anything remaining empty.

82
00:09:21,353 --> 00:09:28,365
Wherefore stand still and waver not, lest turning away from God now for the moment thou never turn back to him again.

83
00:09:28,365 --> 00:09:40,240
Peradventure thou wilt say: ‘Well, Sir, since you are always assuming that some day this birth will happen in me, that the Son will be born in me, can I have any sign whereby to recognise that it has taken place?

84
00:09:40,240 --> 00:09:41,828
Yes, surely!

85
00:09:41,828 --> 00:09:43,640
There would be three signs.

86
00:09:43,640 --> 00:09:45,540
I will tell you one of them.

87
00:09:45,540 --> 00:09:53,215
I am often asked whether it is possible to reach the point of not being hindered by anything in time, either by multiplicity or matter?

88
00:09:53,215 --> 00:09:54,515
Indeed it is!

89
00:09:54,515 --> 00:10:00,065
If this birth really happens no creature can hinder thee, all point thee to God and this birth.

90
00:10:00,065 --> 00:10:03,003
We find in lightning an analogy for this.

91
00:10:03,003 --> 00:10:08,765
Whatever it strikes, whether tree, beast or man, it turns towards itself with the shock.

92
00:10:08,765 --> 00:10:16,190
A man with his back to it instantly flings round to face it; all the thousand leaves of the tree turn over to front the stroke.

93
00:10:16,190 --> 00:10:23,640
So with all whom this birth befalls, they are promptly turned towards this birth with everything present, be it never so earthly.

94
00:10:23,640 --> 00:10:28,103
Nay, even what was formerly a hindrance is now nothing but a help.

95
00:10:28,103 --> 00:10:36,290
Thy face is turned so full towards this birth, no matter what thou dost see and hear, thou receivest nothing save this birth in anything.

96
00:10:36,290 --> 00:10:40,778
All things are simply God to thee who seest only God in all things.

97
00:10:40,778 --> 00:10:46,415
Like one who looks long at the sun, he encounters the sun in whatever he afterwards looks at.

98
00:10:46,415 --> 00:10:52,590
If this is lacking, this looking for and seeing God in all and sundry, then thou lackest this birth.

99
00:10:52,590 --> 00:10:56,903
Thou mayest question: ‘Ought anyone so placed to practise penance?

100
00:10:56,903 --> 00:11:00,978
Does he lose anything by dropping penitential exercises?

101
00:11:01,108 --> 00:11:06,545
Penitential practices, among other things, were instituted for a special object.

102
00:11:06,495 --> 00:11:17,770
Fasting, watching, praying, kneeling, scourging, wearing of hair shirts, hard lying or whatever it may be, were all invented because body and flesh stand ever opposed to spirit.

103
00:11:17,770 --> 00:11:24,258
The body being far too strong for it, there is always battle joined between them, a never-ending conflict.

104
00:11:24,258 --> 00:11:35,545
Here the body is bold and strong for here it is at home; the world helps it, the earth is its fatherland, it is helped by all its kindred: food, drink, ease—all are opposed to spirit.

105
00:11:35,545 --> 00:11:41,908
The spirit is an alien here, in heaven are its kindred, its whole race; there dwell its loved ones.

106
00:11:41,908 --> 00:11:53,495
To succour the spirit in its distress and to impede the flesh somewhat in this strife lest it conquer the spirit, we put upon it the bridle of penitential practices to curb it, so that the spirit can control it.

107
00:11:53,495 --> 00:12:00,945
This is done to bring it to subjection; but to conquer and curb it a thousand times better, put thou upon it the bridle of love.

108
00:12:00,945 --> 00:12:05,983
With love thou overcomest it most surely, with love thou loadest it most heavily.

109
00:12:05,983 --> 00:12:10,358
God lies in wait for us therefore with nothing so much as with love.

110
00:12:10,358 --> 00:12:12,895
For love is like the fisherman’s hook.

111
00:12:12,895 --> 00:12:16,808
To the fisherman falls no fish that is not caught on his hook.

112
00:12:16,808 --> 00:12:24,370
Once it takes the hook the fish is forfeit to the fisherman; in vain it twists hither and thither, the fisherman is certain of his catch.

113
00:12:24,370 --> 00:12:30,545
And so I say of love: he who is caught thereby has the strongest of all bonds and yet a pleasant burden.

114
00:12:30,545 --> 00:12:37,158
He who bears this sweet burden fares further, gets nearer therewith than by using any harshness possible to man.

115
00:12:37,158 --> 00:12:43,270
Moreover, he can cheerfully put up with whatever befalls, cheerfully suffer what God inflicts.

116
00:12:43,270 --> 00:12:48,158
Naught makes thee so much God nor God so much thine own as this sweet bond.

117
00:12:48,158 --> 00:12:51,133
He who has found this way will seek no other.

118
00:12:51,133 --> 00:12:59,045
He who hangs on this hook is so fast caught that foot and hand, mouth, eyes and heart and all that is man’s is bound to be God’s.

119
00:12:59,045 --> 00:13:05,333
So then thou canst not, better than by love, prevail over thy foe and stop him doing thee a mischief.

120
00:13:05,333 --> 00:13:09,520
Wherefore it is written: ‘Love is strong as death and hard as hell.

121
00:13:09,520 --> 00:13:17,933
Death separates soul from body, but love separates all things from the soul; she will not tolerate at any cost what is not God nor God’s.

122
00:13:17,933 --> 00:13:26,845
Who is caught in this net, who walks in this way, whatsoever he works is wrought by love, whose alone the work is: busy or idle it matters nothing.

123
00:13:26,845 --> 00:13:41,245
Such an one’s most trivial action is more profitable, his meanest occupation is more fruitful to himself and other people and to God is better pleasing than the cumulative works of other men, who, though free from mortal sin, are yet inferior to him in love.

124
00:13:41,245 --> 00:13:44,133
He rests more usefully than others labour.

125
00:13:44,133 --> 00:13:50,820
Await thou therefore this hook, so thou be happily caught, and the more surely caught so much the more surely freed.

126
00:13:50,820 --> 00:13:55,720
That we may be thus caught and freed, help us O thou who art love itself.

127
00:13:55,720 --> 00:13:56,633
Amen.
